## The Four Pillars of Harness Engineering

Based on synthesis across all sources, harness engineering breaks down into four pillars:

### 1. Context Engineering (Preparing the Agent's World)

| Source | Technique | Description |
|--------|-----------|-------------|
| **Anthropic** | Initializer Agent | First session sets up `init.sh`, `claude-progress.txt`, feature list, initial git commit |
| **LangChain** | `LocalContextMiddleware` | Auto-discovers directory structure, available tools, Python installations on agent start |
| **OpenAI** | `AGENTS.md` | A codebase guide generated by Codex that tells future agents how to navigate the repo |
| **OpenAI** | Agent Legibility | Codebase and docs optimized so agents can reason about the full business domain from the repo |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Key Principle:** The agent should never have to "guess" what happened before it started. The harness should pre-load everything the agent needs to orient itself.

### 2. Self-Verification & Testing

The **single biggest improvement** across all sources was forcing agents to verify their own work:

| Source | Technique | Impact |
|--------|-----------|--------|
| **LangChain** | `PreCompletionChecklistMiddleware` | Intercepts agent before exit, forces a verification pass against task spec |
| **LangChain** | Build → Verify → Fix loop | Prompt agents to run tests, read output, compare against spec (not own code) |
| **Anthropic** | Feature test list (JSON) | 200+ features marked pass/fail; agent must change status only by testing |
| **Anthropic** | Browser automation | Puppeteer MCP for end-to-end testing as a real user would |
| **OpenAI** | Observability stack | Logs, metrics, traces exposed to Codex so it can verify performance goals |

> [!TIP]
> Anthropic found that using **JSON** for the feature list (instead of Markdown) prevented the model from inappropriately rewriting or deleting tests.

### 3. Failure Mode Mitigation

All sources identified and addressed specific agent failure patterns:

| Failure Mode | Solution | Source |
|-------------|----------|--------|
| **One-shotting** (trying to do everything at once) | Incremental feature-by-feature work | Anthropic |
| **Premature completion** (declaring "done" too early) | `PreCompletionChecklistMiddleware`, forced verification | LangChain, Anthropic |
| **Doom loops** (same broken approach 10+ times) | `LoopDetectionMiddleware` — tracks per-file edit counts | LangChain |
| **Context exhaustion** (running out of window mid-task) | Compaction + clean commit after each feature | Anthropic |
| **Time wasting** | Time budget warnings injected into context | LangChain |
| **Poor search/navigation** | Pre-loaded directory context, `AGENTS.md` | LangChain, OpenAI |

### 4. Multi-Session Persistence

Anthropic's most novel contribution is the **two-agent architecture for long-running tasks**:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│               FIRST SESSION                      │
│  ┌──────────────────────────────┐               │
│  │ Initializer Agent            │               │
│  │ • Set up init.sh             │               │
│  │ • Create claude-progress.txt │               │
│  │ • Generate feature_list.json │               │
│  │ • Initial git commit         │               │
│  └──────────────────────────────┘               │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
              ↓ (clean state)
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│          EVERY SUBSEQUENT SESSION                │
│  ┌──────────────────────────────┐               │
│  │ Coding Agent                 │               │
│  │ 1. pwd → orient              │               │
│  │ 2. Read progress + git log   │               │
│  │ 3. Read feature_list.json    │               │
│  │ 4. Run init.sh → start server│               │
│  │ 5. Test existing features    │               │
│  │ 6. Pick next feature → build │               │
│  │ 7. Test new feature E2E      │               │
│  │ 8. Commit + update progress  │               │
│  └──────────────────────────────┘               │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

> *"Imagine a software project staffed by engineers working in shifts, where each new engineer arrives with no memory of what happened on the previous shift."* — Anthropic

